10. When a child is separated from a parent and rendered unaccompanied, the child's legal

case is generally severed from the parent's. Under the Trafficking Victims Protection

Reauthorization Act of 2008, unaccompanied alien children are entitled to be heard in

removal proceedings before an Immigration Judge. A separated child has his or her own

removal case, separate from the parent's matter, which may be expedited and may not be

1

referred to the Immigration Court. Thus, the child's and parent's cases may proceed as

2
two separate matters, often in different tribunals and on very different schedules,
3 although the family members may share in common underlying facts, claims for relief,
4
and evidence.
5

6

