1 20. ARIMA modeling is important for our purposes here given the data on the
2 monthly number of U.S. Border Patrol apprehensions of family units at the Southwest border
3 exhibit seasonal trends. The figure below is a stacked line graph that shows the cumulative
4 number of U.S. Border Patrol apprehensions of family units at the Southwest border by month
5 from 2012 to 2017.14 As the figure shows, a strong seasonal trend emerges in 2014, wherein the
6 monthly number of U.S. Border Patrol apprehensions of family units at the Southwest border
7 increases beginning late-Winter (February and March) and continues to increase through Spring
8 (April, May, and June) before declining at the start Summer (July). The figure also shows that a
9 second peak may be emerging in Fall (October, November, December), however, it is too soon
10 to tell if this trend will hold given 2017 was the first year in the time series that we saw large
11 numbers of U.S. Border Patrol apprehensions of family units during these months.
